
Topic ----> Hello World !!!!




Question-1)   What does Babel do? 
 

 Solution -:   Compiles JSX into Javascript                                                                                                                                                                          1  B
 


Question-2)  What does the webpack do?
 

 Solution -: A module bundler   




Question-3)   At most, how many default export statements can a module have?
  

 Solution -:   1 




Question-4) Is JSX necessary to work with React?

 
  Solution -:  False  




Question-5) How do you call a function fetch() in JSX?

 
  Solution -:    {fetch()}





Question-6) Which of the following can be used to check if a user is logged in or not?


  Solution :    <div>{loggedIn ? username : 'Hello World'}</div>




 



            !!!!!! Assignment !!!!!!



Question-1)   Everything in react is a __________
 
 

 Solution -:   component                                                                                                                                                                          1  B
 


Question-2) Choose the correct syntax for importing.

Options


This problem may have one or more correct answers

import GIVEN_NAME from ADDRESS
import { NAMED_PARA } from ADDRESS
import GIVEN_NAME, { NAMED_PARA, ... } from ADDRESS
import required {NAMED_PARA } from ADDRESS
 

 Solution -:    import GIVEN_NAME from ADDRESS
import { NAMED_PARA } from ADDRESS
import GIVEN_NAME, { NAMED_PARA, ... } from ADDRESS




Question-3) Which tool is used to take JSX and convert it into createElement calls?
 
Options
   
JSX editor
Browser
ReactDOM
Babel
  

 Solution -:   Babel 




Question-4) Which among the following package contains render() function that renders a react element tree to the DOM?

 
  Solution -:    ReactDOM




Question-5) What is the use of render() in React?

 
  Solution -:    It renders a React element into the DOM in the supplied container and returns a reference to the component.

Further Readings: https://reactjs.org/docs/rendering-elements.html





  
  
